%N A390820 Numbers k such that there is a primitive right triangle with perimeter + inradius = k^2.
%C A390820 Solutions to 2*m^2 + 3*m*n - n^2 = k^2 where m and n are coprime and one of m and n is even.
%C A390820 The first term that arises in more than one way is 2678, which comes from m=1681, n=322 and m=1769, n=178.
%H A390820 Robert Israel, <a href="/A390820/b390820.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..4600</a>
%e A390820 a(3) = 43 is a term because with m = 26 and n = 7, the primitive right triangle with sides a = m^2 - n^2 = 627, b = 2*m*n = 364 and c = m^2 + n^2 = 725 has perimeter a+b+c = 1716, inradius (a+b-c)/2 = 133 and perimeter + inradius = 1716 + 133 = 1849 = 43^2.
%p A390820 N:= 1000: # for terms <= N
%p A390820 R:= {}:
%p A390820 for m from 1 while m^2 < N^2 do
%p A390820   for n from 1+(m mod 2) to m-1 by 2 do
%p A390820     v:= 2*m^2 + 3*m*n - n^2; if v > N^2 then break fi;
%p A390820     if igcd(m,n) = 1 and issqr(v) then
%p A390820       y:= sqrt(v);
%p A390820       R:= R union {y}
%p A390820     fi
%p A390820 od od:
%p A390820 sort(convert(R,list));
